observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management:
 Require the City Treasury Department (CTD) and City Accounting Department (CAD) to prepare a coordinated action plan containing the options and possible solutions to address the audit findings concerning the CIB accounts, and to consider the following:
 Issue a follow-up request with the banks concerned for documents/ information, copy furnished the head offices, for the possibility of securing related archived documents/ information; 
 Intensify efforts in the verification/validation of the dormant accounts to see the possibility of closing the accounts.  Consolidate the balances of the bank accounts with the same purpose/source of funding;
 Reconcile the City’s records with the records of the source agencies regarding the dormant accounts under Trust Fund (TF) transferred from NGAs to facilitate the return of the balances to the source agencies concerned;
 Ensure that the City’s reported cash accounts are adequately backed up with confirmed bank balances and duly supported with appropriate documents, and timely address issues affecting the cash in bank accounts; and
 Effect the necessary adjustment/s in the books of accounts, upon receipt of the documents or proof of transactions from the banks concerned and/or as warranted by transaction documents.
 Establish an agreement with the banks to furnish the CTD with the monthly debit and credit memos for the timely recording of reconciling items; and  
 Require the CAD to prepare the BRS for all bank accounts in compliance with Sections 3.2 and 3.4 of COA Circular No. 96-011.
 Strictly monitor all bank accounts to avoid dormancy and escheat order/s, which are conditions affecting cash management; 
 Apply for the reactivation of the account reported to the Treasurer of the Philippines as unclaimed balances pursuant to Treasury Circular No. 01-2020 dated April 8, 2010, or the Uniform Rules and Procedures for Reactivation of Unclaimed Balances Reported to the Treasurer of the Philippines; and
 Require the CTD to send written notice to the payee of the existence of the check at least one month before a check becomes stale, pursuant to 
Section 59, Chapter 3 of the MNGAS for LGUs, Volume I.

We recommended that Management require the CAD to:
Immediately submit the lacking documents to the ORD, LGAS-NCR pertaining to the 11 dormant accounts to facilitate the proper resolution of the request for write-off thereto, pursuant to COA Circular No. 2023-008 dated August 17, 2023;
Employ other means of coordinating with the concerned NGAs, GOCCs, and other LGUs to obtain pertinent information and records related to the dormant liability accounts;
In case efforts become futile, as regards the accounts with NGAs, GOCCs, and other LGUs, the Management may consider initiating a request for write-off of these dormant liability accounts pursuant to COA Circular No. 2023-008, for the fair reporting of account balances in the financial statements; and
Effect the necessary adjusting entries upon grant of the authority to write off/derecognize dormant account/s pursuant to COA Circular No. 2023-008.

We recommended that Management review its records and make necessary adjustments as warranted.

The total balance of the SLs for each supplier do not reconcile with the balance of the Accounts Payable accounts as of year-end, due to: (a) checks drawn but not yet issued to the payee were automatically recorded in the accounting system as deduction in the Cash in Bank account and the Accounts Payable account; (b) Unreleased checks as of year-end were not reversed to the individual SLs of each affected supplier; and (c) Reports of Checks Issued (RCI) submitted by the CTD to the CAD were not  based on the actual checks issued to the payee, contrary to Annex 6,  Section 43 of the MNGAS for LGUs, hence, the actual outstanding payable to the suppliers concerned as of year-end were not reflected in the SLs, which cast doubt on the accuracy of the balance of the Accounts Payable account as of December 31, 2024.

We recommended that Management:
Coordinate with the system provider to apply necessary changes in the accounting system to comply with the requirements of the NGAS Manual for LGUs;
Revisit the existing accounting system’s processes to address the issues raised with the end view of complying with the requirements of the MNGAS for LGUs;
Effect the adjusting entries to individual SLs to reflect the actual outstanding balance as of year-end;
Require the CTD to prepare and submit to CAD a RCI with information of checks that have been physically released and issued to payees; and
Require the CAD and CTD to apply necessary controls in the process and conduct regular reconciliation of records.

We recommended that Management require:

CAD to:

strictly enforce the liquidation of CAs granted to AOs within the reglementary period and to enforce the liquidation of CAs in compliance with Item 5.8 of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997, and impose the sanctions provided in Item 5.9 of the same COA Circular, as warranted by the circumstances;





substantiate the request for write-off for the amount of P4,817,495.00, strictly complying with the requirements of COA Circular No. 2016-005, as amended by COA Circular No. 2023-008 dated August 17, 2023; 



City Legal Department (CLD) to recommend appropriate action to be taken in the case of AOs who are already separated from the service; and




The City Administrator to constantly remind officials and employees concerned of the pertinent laws, rules, and regulations governing the handling of cash advances every time they are granted with cash advance.

We recommended that Management require the CAD to:

Coordinate with the NGAs, GOCCs and other LGUs concerned regarding the dormant accounts to be able to gather relevant information and documents as basis of the City’s subsequent action;  

In case such effort proves to be of no help, Management may consider initiating a request for the write-off of the dormant accounts pursuant to COA Circular No. 2023-008 dated 
August 17, 2023, which provides the guidelines on the proper disposition of dormant accounts of LGUs, among others, amending COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016, to fast track the cleansing of dormant accounts of government agencies for the fair presentation of accounts in the financial statements; 

Effect the necessary adjusting entries upon the grant of the authority to write off/derecognition of the dormant account/s pursuant to COA Circular No. 2023-008; and



Implement a suitable monitoring and review process to ensure the timely liquidation/settlement of accounts with other government agencies with full documentation to forestall dormancy of accounts.

We recommended that Management require the CAD to:

Address the audit findings concerning the cash in bank accounts and dormant unliquidated CAs;

Analyze the accounts Due from Other Funds and the Due to Other Funds more diligently and transfer funds to the TF from the GF, as a result of reconciliation and adjustments to be made;

Immediately transfer cash to establish funding when a receivable is set up and the corresponding obligation taken up in the TF books; and

Ensure that the TF have the corresponding cash at all times to guarantee the fulfillment of the purpose for which the trust was created, or the funds received.

We recommended that Management:


Require the City Treasury Department (CTD) and the City Accounting Department (CAD) to prepare a coordinated action plan containing the options and possible solutions to address the audit findings concerning the CIB accounts, and to consider the following:

Intensify efforts in the verification/validation of these dormant accounts to see the possibility of closing these accounts.  Consolidate the balances with the bank accounts for the same purpose/source of funding;

Issue a follow up request with the banks concerned for documents/ information, copy furnished the head offices, for the possibility of securing related archived documents/ information;

Reconcile the City’s records with the records of the source agencies regarding the dormant accounts under Trust Fund (TF) transferred from (National Government Agencies) NGAs to facilitate the return of the balances to the source agencies concerned;

Ensure that the City’s cash accounts are adequately backed up with confirmed bank balances and duly supported with appropriate documents, and to timely address issues affecting the cash in bank accounts; and

Effect the necessary adjustment/s in the books of accounts, upon receipt of the documents or proof of transactions from the banks concerned and/or as warranted by transaction documents and reconciliation efforts.

Require the CTD to strictly monitor all bank accounts to avoid dormancy and escheat order/s, which are conditions affecting cash management; 

Establish an agreement with the banks to furnish the CTD with the monthly debit and credit memos for the timely recording of reconciling items;  

Require the CAD to prepare the BRS for all bank accounts in compliance with Sections 3.2 and 3.4 of COA Circular No. 96-011; 

Require the CTD to make an arrangement with the bank for the monthly release of bank statements; and

Immediately transfer the bank account deposits from PNB to any of the AGDBs or opt to obtain clearance/approval from the Bureau of Local Government Finance should the City wishes to retain maintenance of their current deposits with PNB pursuant to Section 5.2.2. of DOF Circular No. 02-2022.

We recommended that Management require the CAD to:

Address the audit findings concerning the cash in bank accounts and dormant unliquidated CAs;

Analyze the accounts Due from Other Funds and the Due to Other Funds more diligently and transfer funds to the TF from the GF, as a result of reconciliation and adjustments to be made;

Immediately transfer cash to establish funding when a receivable is set up and the corresponding obligation taken up in the TF books; and

Ensure that the TF have the corresponding cash at all times to guarantee the fulfillment of the purpose for which the trust was created, or the funds received.

We recommended that Management require the CAD to:
Coordinate with the NGAs, GOCCs and other LGUs concerned regarding the dormant accounts to be able to gather relevant information and documents as basis of the City’s subsequent action;
In case such effort proves to be of no help, Management may consider initiating a request for the write-off of the dormant accounts pursuant to COA Circular No. 2023-008 dated August 17, 2023, which provides the guidelines on the proper disposition of dormant accounts of LGUs, among others, amending COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016, to fast track the cleansing of dormant accounts of government agencies for the fair presentation of accounts in the financial statements;
Effect the necessary adjusting entries upon the grant of the authority to write off/derecognition of the dormant account/s pursuant to COA Circular No. 2023-008; and
Implement a suitable monitoring and review process to ensure the timely liquidation/settlement of accounts with other government agencies with full documentation to forestall dormancy of accounts.

We recommended that Management require:
The CAD to -
Strictly enforce the liquidation of CAs granted to AOs within the reglementary period and immediate refund of any unspent amount;
Submit to the City Legal Officer the cases of the deceased AOs and those who have already resigned and whose location cannot be traced for appropriate legal remedies;
The City Legal Officer to recommend to the City Mayor the appropriate action to be done to recover the unliquidated cash advances; and
We also recommended that Management initiate action to request the write-off of the dormant CAs following the requirements and procedures provided under COA Circular No. 2016-005.

We recommended that the Management require the CAD to:
Set up an effective review level within the CAD so as to detect errors, inaccuracies and oversight in the accounting process, like the completeness of agency assets that are subjected to depreciation, the accuracy of information used, and the timing and computation of depreciation;
Comply with Paragraph 42 of IPSAS 3 with regard to change in accounting estimates;
Observe PAG 3 of IPSAS 17 in the initial recognition of depreciation of PPE; and
Effect the necessary adjustments.

In view of the foregoing, we recommended that Management:
Create a dedicated appraisal committee from the offices/departments concerned to:
Compute and determine the proper value of the removed/replaced costs of parts/materials that need to be derecognized in the books following the provisions of IPSAS and furnish COA a copy of the committee’s appraisal report;
Consider the use of the cost of the replacement as allowed in Paragraph 85 of IPSAS 17, should it be impracticable to determine the carrying amount of the replaced parts;
Include as part of the standard operating procedure, the appraisal of costs of replaced/removed materials whenever there are repairs, renovations or rehabilitations made in any of the City’s buildings; and
Require the CAD to derecognize in the books, the costs of replaced/removed materials incident to the repairs, renovations and rehabilitations made based on the report of the appraisal committee.

We reiterated our previous year’s recommendation that Management require the CAO to:
Exert more effort to locate the supporting documents as well as the whereabouts of the accountable officers with CAs since 2002, in order that appropriate demand letters may be issued thereto;
Strictly monitor the liquidation of CAs by sending demand letters regularly, particularly to accountable officers and employees who are still in active in service  and in case of failure to liquidate the same despite demand, enforce the withholding of payment of any money due them may be made pursuant to COA Circular No. 97-002;
Initiate the filing of appropriate administrative proceedings against the accountable officers who failed to settle their accountabilities after the demand; and
Strictly comply with the general guidelines in the grant and liquidation of CAs under COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997 and Section 89 of PD No. 1445.

We recommended that Management require the:
Responsible offcials to locate the MOAs, SAROs and other pertinent documents to determine the purpose and conditions for the implementation of the PPAs;
CAO to –
to exert extra effort to look for the documents supporting the non-moving balances and ascertain the reasons why the same remained in the books;
to reconcile their records with that of the SAs and request for the utilization of the remaining balances for other related projects, and if not permitted, remit the unutilized balance to the concerned SAs;
reclassify the PCF and PHIC –PCBI totaling P 34,785,116.07 to Due to Government Owned or Controlled Corporations and the Doctors’ fees totaling P4,050,666.34 to Due to Officers and Employees;
Distribute the Doctors’ Professional Fees to the health workers of CCMC in accordance with DOH AO No. 2016-033;
Require the responsible officials to utilize the funds for the intended purpose; and
Provide copies of the MOAs, SAROs and other pertinent documents to the Office of the Auditor to facilitate the evaluation of the PPAs.

We reiterated our previous year’s recommendation that Management require the CAO to: 

Exert extra effort to locate the documents and whereabouts of the accountable officers with CAs since CY 2002 to determine whom to issue the demand letter for the liquidation of CAs;







Strictly monitor the liquidation of CAs by sending demand letters regularly, particularly to accountable officers and employees who are still in active service,  and if the CAs are not utilized, demand refund from the concerned accountable officers;

Strictly comply with the general guidelines in the grant and liquidation of CAs under COA Circulars No. 97-002 and 2012-004, and Section 89 of PD 1445; and

Request for write-off of the long outstanding unliquidated CAs in the event that all remedies have been exhausted, in accordance with the pertinent provisions of COA Circular No. 2016-005.

We recommended that Management require:

The CAO and the GSO, in coordination with the various offices/ departments, to continuously reconcile the variance of the PPE account balances reflected in their respective records, and the CAO to prepare necessary adjustments, if any;  






The CAO to:

Adjust the misclassified accounts and the erroneous/double entries;

Record small tangible items in the respective Inventory accounts and eliminate the same from the PPE balance and the corresponding accumulated depreciation; and

The GSO to issue the corresponding ICS to all the end-users of the small tangible items

We recommended that Management require: 

The concerned implementing offices/departments to implement immediately the various PPAs funded by the NGAs; 




The CAO to - 

Exert extra effort to look for the documents supporting the non-moving balances and ascertain the reasons why the same remained in the books for so long; 



Reconcile their records with the records of the source agencies and request for the utilization of the remaining balances for other related projects, if not, remit the unutilized balance to the concerned source agencies or to the National Treasury;

Maintain SLs for each fund transfer; and


The CAO and responsible officials to provide the City Auditor’s Office with   the exact date the grant/funds were received and the reasons why the said grants/reimbursements were not yet implemented/liquidated and/or distributed to date.

To avoid accumulation of unliquidated cash advances, we have recommended that Management instruct the CAO to:

Demand immediate settlement/liquidation from all accountable officers with outstanding cash advances pursuant to COA Circular No. 97-002 and strictly monitor the liquidation of cash advances;




Initiate the filing of appropriate Administrative Proceedings for Gross Neglect of Duty against those who failed to account for their accountabilities after demand or Simple Neglect of Duty against those who failed to liquidate their cash advances in full within the prescribed period;

Avoid granting additional cash advances unless the previous cash advance given if first settled or a property accounting thereof is made;

Exert more effort to locate the whereabouts of separated accountable officers and issue follow-up demand letters; and

In the event that all remedies have been exhausted to settle the outstanding cash advances to no avail, request for write-off the guidelines under COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016.
